ealer, from dialect <i>hitte</i> ‘goat’.","English (Devon): apparently a variant of   Hett  ; see   Hatt  ."]},{"name":"Hotte","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Lucien, Adelard, Adrien, Jacques, Marcel, Pierrette.","French: from <i>hotte</i>, denoting a type of basket carried on the back, hence a nickname or a metonymic occupational name for someone who carried or made these.","German (<b>Hötte</b>): variant of <b>Hütte</b> (see   Huett   2) or a variant of   Hott  ."]},{"name":"Huetter","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Gerhard, Heinz, Kurt.","German (<b>Hütter</b>):","variant of <b>Hütt</b> (see   Huett   2), with the addition of the agent suffix <i>-er</i>."]},{"name":"Huettl","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Alfons, Erhard, Othmar.","South German (<b>Hüttl</b>): diminutive of <b>Hütt</b> (see   Huett   2)."]},{"name":"Hewitt","meanings":["English:","from the Middle English personal name <i>Hewet</i>, <i>Huet</i>, <i>Hughet</i>, <i>Howet</i>, pet forms of <i>Hugh</i> (Middle English <i>Hewe</i>, <i>Hue</i>; see   Hugh   and compare   Hew  ). The spelling <i>Hughet</i> stood for both <i>Huet</i> and the synonymous <i>Huget</i>; see   Huggett  . This surname has also been established in Ireland since the 14th century.","habitational name from Hewitts in Chelsfield or Hewitts in Willesborough (both Kent), both named from Old English <i>hīewett</i> ‘cutting’, denoting a place where trees had been cut down. Here there lived families called <i>de la Hewatte</i> (1270), <i>de la hewett</i> (1301), and <i>atte Hewete</i> (1338). The name may also be topographic for someone who lived in a newly made clearing in a wood."]}]},{"name":"Christiana","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval learned feminine form of   Christian .  As a recent revival it represents an elaborated form of   Christina .  It is also sometimes spelled  <b>Christianna</b> , under the influence of the name   Anna ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":8,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Christiana Huett was born in 1447, in Maidwell, Northamptonshire, England as the daughter of Thomas Huett. She married Thomas Haselwood about 1476, in Maidwell, Northamptonshire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 3 daughters. She died in 1500, in her hometown, at the age of 53."},"et":{"1447–1500":"1447–1500","1444–1507":"1444–1507","1479–1492":"1479–1492","1480–1540":"1480–1540","1481–1490":"1481–1490","1483–1520":"1483–1520","1485–Male":"1485–Surnud","1421–1500":"1421–1500","9 April 1480":"9. aprill 1480","1483":"1483","1481":"1481","1492":"1492","1480":"1480","1490":"1490","1447":"1447","1479":"1479","1500":"1500","1455":"1455","1444":"1444","1421":"1421","1520":"1520","1485":"1485","1540":"1540","about 1476":"umbes 1476","1507":"1507","Maidwell, Northampton, England, Great Britain":"Maidwell, Northamptonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Maidwell, Northampton, England":"Maidwell, Northamptonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Drayton, Worcestershire, England":"Drayton, Worcestershire, England","Maidwell, Northamptonshire, England":"Maidwell, Northamptonshire, England"},"fi":{"1447–1500":"1447–1500","1444–1507":"1444–1507","1479–1492":"1479–1492","1480–1540":"1480–1540","1481–1490":"1481–1490","1483–1520":"1483–1520","1485–Male":"1485–Kuollut","1421–1500":"1421–1500","9 April 1480":"9. huhtikuuta 1480","1483":"1483","1481